83: The Catholic holy days of obligation vary by country, but generally include the following major days:
The Solemnity of Jesus Christ, King of the Universe, which is celebrated on the last Sunday of the liturgical year, usually in late November or early December in many countries.
The Feast of the Immaculate Conception of the Blessed Virgin Mary, observed on December 8th, celebrating the belief that Mary was conceived without original sin.
The Nativity of Our Lord Jesus Christ, or Christmas, celebrated on December 25th, commemorating the birth of Jesus Christ.
The Feast of Saint Joseph, Spouse of the Blessed Virgin Mary, observed on March 19th in many countries, honoring Saint Joseph, the foster father of Jesus.
The Feast of the Annunciation of the Lord, celebrated on March 25th, marking the angel Gabriel's announcement to Mary that she would conceive Jesus.
The Feast of the Ascension of Jesus Christ, observed forty days after Easter, usually on a Thursday, commemorating Jesus' ascension into heaven.
The Feast of Pentecost, celebrated fifty days after Easter, marking the descent of the Holy Spirit upon the apostles.
The Feast of the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, observed on August 15th, celebrating Mary's assumption into heaven.
The Feast of All Saints, celebrated on November 1st, honoring all saints, known and unknown.
The Feast of All Souls, observed on November 2nd, praying for the souls of the deceased.

In some countries, additional days are considered holy days of obligation, such as the Feast of the Sacred Heart of Jesus or the Feast of the Transfiguration, but these can vary depending on local episcopal conference decisions.
